Let \mathbb {F}=\Bbbk ^{H}. We see if H\leq \mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F}), then |H|\leq |\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F})|\leq [\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}] (where the last inequality follows by Size of automorphism group for finite extension is not greater than the degree of the finite extension). We also see that [\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}]\leq |H|. Hence |H|=|\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F})|=[\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}]. Moreover, H=\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F}). Since |\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F})|=[\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}], it follows that \Bbbk / \mathbb {F} is Galois.

Let \mathbb {F}=\Bbbk ^{H}. We see if H\leq \mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F}), then |H|\leq |\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F})|\leq [\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}] (where the last inequality follows by Size of automorphism group for finite extension is not greater than the degree of the finite extension). We also see that [\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}]\leq |H|. Hence |H|=|\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F})|=[\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}]. Moreover, H=\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F}). Since |\mathop {	extrm {Aut}}
olimits (\Bbbk / \mathbb {F})|=[\Bbbk : \mathbb {F}], it follows that \Bbbk / \mathbb {F} is Galois.

Recall the Galois correspondence looks like
\begin {split}\left \{\begin {matrix}\hbox {subgroups}\\\hbox {of }\mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk )\end {matrix}\right \}&\to \left \{\begin {matrix}\hbox {subfields}\\\hbox {of }\Bbbk \end {matrix}\right \}\\ H&\mapsto \Bbbk ^{H}\end {split}
and
\begin {split}\left \{\begin {matrix}\hbox {subfields}\\\hbox {of }\Bbbk \end {matrix}\right \}&\to \left \{\begin {matrix}\hbox {subgroups}\\\hbox {of }\mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk )\end {matrix}\right \}\\ \mathbb {F} & \mapsto \mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {F})\end {split}
This corollary says composing these maps H\mapsto \Bbbk ^{H}\mapsto \mathop {\textrm {Aut}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \Bbbk ^{H}) is the identity map.
